definition: a fruit produced by an apple tree
exampleSentence: She ate an apple for a snack.

definition: a written or printed work consisting of pages glued or sewn together along one side and bound in covers
exampleSentence: She loves to read a good book before bed.
origin: Old Englishbōc, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch boek and German Buch.

definition: a road vehicle, typically with four wheels, powered by an internal combustion engine and able to carry a small number of people
exampleSentence: He drives a red car to work every day.
origin: Middle Englishcarre, from Old Northern French, based on Latin carrum, carrus, of Celtic origin.

definition: an electronic device for storing and processing data, typically in binary form, according to instructions given to it in a variable program
exampleSentence: She uses her computer to browse the internet and check emails.
origin: Late 19th century: from French ordinateur, from Latin computare ‘compute’.

definition: vocal or instrumental sounds (or both) combined in such a way as to produce beauty of form, harmony, and expression of emotion
exampleSentence: Listening to music can improve mood and reduce stress.
origin: Middle English: from Old Frenchmusique, via Latin from Greek mousikē (tekhnē) ‘(art) of the Muses’, from mousa ‘muse’.
